## Legislative and Regulatory Responses

### Existing Laws and Their Limitations

| Law/Act                                 | Provisions                                                                                       | Limitations                                                                                   |
|----------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Revolving Door Act (Pre-2015)**      | Senators banned from lobbying for 2 years; House members for 1 year after leaving office ([Course Hero, 2017](https://www.coursehero.com/file/72164050/REVOLVING-DOORSdocx/)). | Short cooling-off periods; loopholes such as strategic consulting allow circumvention.       |
| **Close Revolving Door Act (2015)**    | Prohibits Senators and Representatives from lobbying immediately upon retirement ([Course Hero, 2017](https://www.coursehero.com/file/72164050/REVOLVING-DOORSdocx/)). | Enforcement challenges; limited scope; does not cover all lobbying activities or branches.   |
| **Disclosure Act (1995) & Honest Leadership and Open Government Act (2007)** | Require lobbyists to disclose activities and limit undue influence ([Alina’s Blog, 2012](https://alinagtran.blogspot.com/2012/12/should-former-members-of-congress-be.html)). | Disclosure alone does not prevent influence; enforcement varies; loopholes remain.           |

### State-Level Innovations

Some states have implemented more stringent rules, including:

- Banning former officials from lobbying any branch of government for a period after leaving office ([Public Citizen, 2019](https://www.citizen.org/article/slowing-the-federal-revolving-door/)).

- Closing loopholes that allow lobbying across branches, recognizing the interconnectedness of legislative and executive functions ([Public Citizen, 2019](https://www.citizen.org/article/slowing-the-federal-revolving-door/)).

